BRIEF INTRODUCTION

This rmarkdown is based on data analysis on lowerback pain symptoms dataset.Primarily, it will summarize all insights gained by performing data analysis steps on lowerback pain dataset.This rmarkdown is divided the concrete modules of data analysis into three steps: 1) Data Cleaning and exploration 2) Data Visualization 3) Prediction model(Decision Tree,Naive Bayes,SVM,Random forest)

Eventually, it will also compare the distinct prediction models on the basis of Accuracy,Precision, Recall, and F measure etc.

Firstly, to implement all the steps mentioned above importing the dataset is required.

Data Source the dataset has been downloded from Kaggle official website ( https://www.kaggle.com/sammy123/lower-back-pain-symptoms-dataset).

#importing dataset
Spine_Data<-read.csv("~/Dataset_spine.csv", sep=",", header = TRUE)

1.DATA CLEANING AND EXPLORATION

Intially, it is important to check the number of rows and columns present in the entire dataset. dim() provides the information that there are 310 observation in dataset and 14 columns. The dataset comprises of 12 different features and 13th column classifies the data into two classes Abnormal, Normal.Also, all the features consist numeric data. While, inspecting the data set i realized that the 14th column holds unnecessary information. So, I removed that column from the dataset.

2. DATA VISUALIZATION

2.1 number of people with Abnormal/Normal Spine

# plot the number of people with Abnormal/Normal Spine
ggplot(Spine_Data, aes(x = Class_Att,fill= Class_Att)) + geom_bar()+ xlab("Spine")+ ylab("No. of People")+ggtitle("Number of people with Abnormal/Normal Spine")

The above barchart depicts that the people with abnormal spine are significantly more than the people with normal Spine.

2.2

univariate visualization These visualizations helps to understand the featues/attributes independently. multiviarate visualizations ### Box And Whisker Plots By Class Density by class

# bloxplot to detect outliers
x <- Spine_Data[,1:12]
y <- Spine_Data[,13]
featurePlot(x = x, 
           y = y, 
           plot = "box",
           scales = list(y = list(relation="free"),
                         x = list(rot = 90)),
           auto.key = list(columns = 2),main="Boxplot for all the Spine features")

This feature plot compares the features of lower back pain. It reveals that distribution of data and helps to identify the outliers in the data.Basically, outliers are the data values that are far from other data values in the dataset.The outliers can affect the results.However, here i am not deleting the outliers. It is clear from the visualization that most of the outliers are present in Pelvic_radius,Degree_spondylolisthesis,Pelvic_incidence,Pelvic_tilt feature.Apart from this, few outliers were also found in Lumbar_lordosis_angle and Sacral_slope.Conversly, the reamaining features do not have any outliers. The boxplots depicts that Degree_spondylolisthesis is an important feature in the datset. Its value remain zero for normal Spine but as it goes higher then it is resposible for Abnormal class. It is also noticed that when Pelvic_incidence, Pelvic_tilt,Lumbar_lordosis_angle, Sacral_slope, and Pelvic_radius has higher value that it accountable for Abnormal Spine.On the other hand, Thoracic_slope,Cervical_tilt,Sacrum_angle,Scoliosis_slope,Pelvic_slope,and Direct_tilt does not really helps to differentiate for normal/abnormal Spine. This is because the expected range of data is approximately same.

Density by class

Correlation Plot by class

In the dot representation, blue indicates the positive correlation and the red shows the negative correlation. The bigger the dot the larger the relation.Here,The diagonal are perfectly positively correlated because it shows the correlation of each attribute with itself.

Correlation Plot for Abnormal_Spine

# finding correlation using ggcorr
subset1<-subset(Spine_Data, Spine_Data$Class_Att=="Abnormal")
p1 <-cor(subset1[,1:12])
title <- "Correlation in features W.R.T. Abnormal Spine"
corrplot(p1, method = "circle", order="hclust", addrect=2, title = title,mar=c(0,0,1,0) )

This plot indicates the strong postive correlation between Degree_spondylolisthesis, lumbar_lordosis_angle,Pelvic_incidence, sarcal_slope.It derives that these correalated are responsible for Abnormal Spine.

Correlation Plot for Normal_Spine

subset2<-subset(Spine_Data, Spine_Data$Class_Att=="Normal")
p2 <-cor(subset2[,1:12])
corrplot(p2, method = "circle", order="hclust", addrect=2 ,title = "Correlation in features W.R.T. Normal Spine" ,mar=c(0,0,1,0)  )

From the above plot, it can be clearly seen that lumbar_lordosis_angle and Pelvic_incidence has positive corelation with Pelvic_incedence, Pelvic_tilt,and sarcal_slope.On the flipside, Pelvic_radius has negative correlation with lumbar_lordosis_angle, Pelvic_incidence,sarcal_slope and Pelvic_tilt.It implies that these correlated features are liable for normal Spine.

PREDICTION MODELS

Decision Tree Model

First of all, here the data is divided the data into two groups - the training set, and the test set. The training data is used to build the tree, and the test data is used to examine how well it performed.

# "seed" a random number generator 
set.seed(1234)

# Split the data into 70% training, 30% test
ind <- sample(2, nrow(Spine_Data), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7, 0.3))
train_data <- Spine_Data[ind==1,]
test_data <- Spine_Data[ind==2,]

The formula dataframe below defines that Class_Att is the target variable, and all the other variables are independent variables.

#classify Spine data 
formula <- Class_Att ~ Degree_spondylolisthesis + Pelvic_incidence + Pelvic_tilt + Lumbar_lordosis_angle + Pelvic_radius + Sacral_slope + Cervical_tilt + Pelvic_slope + Direct_tilt + Thoracic_slope + Sacrum_angle + Scoliosis_slope

Spine_Data_ctree <- ctree(formula, data = train_data)
plot(Spine_Data_ctree)

In the above decision tree,the split criteria for root node is Degree_spondylolisthesis. If the Degree_spondylolisthesis is less than 13.928, then there is 99% chances that Spine Specimen is classified as Abnormal.However, Degree_spondylolisthesis is less than 13.928 and if the Pelvic_radius is less than 125.213, then there is 80% probability that it can be normal Spine. Moreover, if Sarcal_slope is greater than 40.75 then 70% chances that it leads to Abnormal Spine. On the contrary, if Sarcal_slope less than 40.75 then there is 70% chances it result in normal_Spine.

table(predict(Spine_Data_ctree, newdata = test_data), test_data$Class_Att)
##           
##            Abnormal Normal
##   Abnormal       57     10
##   Normal          1     19

The prediction model made 10 errors by classifying speciments of normal as abnormal.Also, it made 1 error for Abnormal class by classifying as normal.The main diagonal values shows the correct number of classification for each class.

confusionMatrix(predict(Spine_Data_ctree, newdata = test_data), test_data$Class_Att)

The accuracy of Decision tree model is 87.36% which is quite high. Naive Bayes Model

# load the libraries
library(caret)
library(klaR)

# define an 70/30 train/test split of the dataset
split=0.70
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(Spine_Data$Class_Att, list=FALSE)
data_train <- Spine_Data[ trainIndex,]
data_test <- Spine_Data[-trainIndex,]
# train a naive bayes model
model <- NaiveBayes(Class_Att~., data=data_train, kernel="linear" , scale=FALSE)

# make predictions
x_test <- data_test[,1:12]

y_test <- data_test[,13]

predictions <- predict(model, x_test)

# summarize results
confusionMatrix(predictions$class, y_test)
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics

Random Forest

#Random Forest Algorithm
# Split the data into 70% training, 30% test
set.seed(123)
ind <- sample(2, nrow(Spine_Data), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7, 0.3))
train_data <- Spine_Data[ind==1,]
test_data <- Spine_Data[ind==2,]
#random forest model for dataset 
RF_model <- randomForest(Class_Att~., data = train_data , ntree= 100, proximity = T)
print(RF_model)
